# Agent-Based Generative UI: Architecture and Implementation

Based on the documentation provided, here's a comprehensive overview of building generative UI with agents:

## Overall Architecture

The system uses a three-layer approach:

1. **Catalog Definition**: Components available to the AI, with Zod schemas
2. **Registry Binding**: Maps catalog components to actual implementations
3. **Agent Integration**: AI generates JSON specs via structured output

The documentation emphasizes: *"The catalog acts as a guardrail: the AI can only use components you've defined, with props that match your schema."*

## Frontend-to-Agent Connection

The frontend connects via `useStream`, extracting the UI specification from tool calls:

```tsx
const stream = useStream<typeof myAgent>({
  apiUrl: "http://localhost:2024",
  assistantId: "generative_ui",
});

const aiMessage = stream.messages.find(AIMessage.isInstance);
const rawSpec = aiMessage?.tool_calls?.[0]?.args;
```

The agent returns structured output containing the UI spec in its tool call arguments.

## Streaming and Progressive Rendering

During streaming, components arrive incrementally. The frontend filters incomplete elements and uses `loading={true}`:

```tsx
const spec = (() => {
  if (!rawSpec?.root || !rawSpec?.elements) return null;
  const rootEl = rawSpec.elements[rawSpec.root];
  if (!rootEl?.type || rootEl?.props == null) return null;

  const safeElements = {};
  for (const [key, el] of Object.entries(rawSpec.elements)) {
    if (el?.type && el?.props != null) {
      safeElements[key] = el;
    }
  }
  return { root: rawSpec.root, elements: safeElements };
})();

return (
  <JSONUIProvider registry={registry}>
    <Renderer spec={spec} registry={registry} loading={stream.isLoading} />
  </JSONUIProvider>
);
```

The `Renderer` silently skips incomplete children during streaming, allowing users to see the UI build up in real time.

## Catalog Definition Example

```ts
const catalog = defineCatalog(schema, {
  components: {
    Card: {
      description: "A card container with optional title and padding",
      props: z.object({
        title: z.string().optional(),
        padding: z.enum(["sm", "md", "lg"]).optional(),
      }),
    },
    TextInput: {
      description: "A text input field with optional label and placeholder",
      props: z.object({
        label: z.string().optional(),
        placeholder: z.string().optional(),
        type: z.enum(["text", "email", "password", "number", "textarea"]).optional(),
      }),
    },
    Button: {
      description: "A clickable button with label and style variants",
      props: z.object({
        label: z.string(),
        variant: z.enum(["primary", "secondary", "ghost", "link"]).optional(),
        fullWidth: z.boolean().optional(),
      }),
    },
  },
  actions: {},
});
```

## Registry Implementation (React Example)

```tsx
const { registry } = defineRegistry(catalog, {
  components: {
    Card: ({ props, children }) => (
      <div className="card">
        {props.title && <h2>{props.title}</h2>}
        {children}
      </div>
    ),
    TextInput: ({ props }) => (
      <div>
        {props.label && <label>{props.label}</label>}
        <input type={props.type ?? "text"} placeholder={props.placeholder} />
      </div>
    ),
    Button: ({ props }) => (
      <button className={props.variant ?? "primary"}>
        {props.label}
      </button>
    ),
  },
});
```

## Generated UI Specification Format

The agent produces a flat JSON structure with a root reference and element map:

```json
{
  "root": "login-card",
  "elements": {
    "login-card": {
      "type": "Card",
      "props": { "title": "Login" },
      "children": ["login-stack"]
    },
    "login-stack": {
      "type": "Stack",
      "props": { "direction": "vertical", "gap": "md" },
      "children": ["email-input", "password-input", "submit-btn"]
    },
    "email-input": {
      "type": "TextInput",
      "props": { "label": "Email", "placeholder": "Enter your email", "type": "email" },
      "children": []
    }
  }
}
```

## Key Implementation Differences

**Agent-based approach** (documented here):
- Uses structured tool calls to return UI specs
- Validates against the catalog schema server-side
- Supports streaming with progressive rendering
- Framework-agnostic (React, Vue, Svelte, Angular)

This differs from direct LLM approaches by enforcing type safety through Zod schemas and limiting the AI to predefined components.

## Critical Best Practices

- *"Keep catalogs focused. Include only components the AI needs for the use case."*
- Always validate that elements have `type` and non-null `props` before rendering
- Use `JSONUIProvider` to wrap the `Renderer` for context setup
- Employ CSS custom properties for theme adaptation
- Pass `loading={true}` during streaming for graceful incomplete-child handling

